## Phase 7 — Provider Health Checker

**Goal:** Automated circuit breaking when a provider is down.

### Step 25 — Deploy the health checker module

The health checker is a standalone Lambda in its own Terraform module (`terraform/modules/health_checker/`).
The handler lives at `ai-platform/ai_platform/health_checker.py` — it ships inside the same zip as the gateway.

```bash
cd terraform
terraform apply -target=module.health_checker
```

This creates:
- A separate Lambda function `ai-platform-health-checker-production`
- An EventBridge rule `rate(5 minutes)` to invoke it
- IAM permissions scoped to the health DynamoDB table and Secrets Manager ARNs

> **Bedrock model note:** `amazon.titan-text-lite-v1` does not exist in all AWS accounts.
> If you see `ResourceNotFoundException` when testing Bedrock, check which models are active:
> ```bash
> aws bedrock list-foundation-models --query "modelSummaries[?contains(modelId,'nova')].{id:modelId,status:modelLifecycle.status}"
> ```
> The platform uses **Amazon Nova Micro** (`amazon.nova-micro-v1:0`) — it's in the `low` tier and
> is cheaper than Titan was. It uses a different API payload format (Messages API with
> `content: [{text: "..."}]` arrays); this is handled in `bedrock_provider.py`.

> **Health table write note:** `mark_failure()` in `health.py` uses a DynamoDB `if_not_exists`
> condition on the `status` field — once a provider is set to "healthy" it will never be
> overwritten to "unhealthy" by that function. The health checker Lambda bypasses this by
> calling `table.put_item()` directly, which always overwrites. `UNHEALTHY_THRESHOLD = 3`
> consecutive failures before a provider is marked down.

**Checkpoint:** Providers are automatically checked every 5 minutes; the router skips unhealthy ones. ✓

